      "note_no": "11",
      "note": "Lit., \"over its backs\" i.e., according to all classical commentators, the \"backs\" of the above-mentioned animals and ships alike, the singular form of the pronoun (\"its\") relating to the collective entity comprised in the concept of \"all whereon you ride\" (ma tarkabun): in other words, \"all that you use or may use by way of transport\". As regards my rendering of li-tasta'u as so that you might gain mastery\", I should like to point out that the verb istawa (lit., \"he established himself) has often the connotation adopted by me: see Jawhari, Raghib and Lisan al-'Arab, art. sawa; also Lane IV, 1478."
